In Spring Data JPA, sometimes findBy methods are not enough for complex queries.
In such cases we use Custom Queries using the @Query annotation.

Custom queries allow us to write JPQL or SQL manually.

1️⃣ What is a Custom Query?

A custom query is a query written manually using @Query inside the repository interface.

Example:

@Query("select e from Employee e")
List<Employee> getEmployees();
2️⃣ Employee Entity Example
@Entity
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Integer empId;

    private String empName;
    private Double salary;
    private String dept;

}
3️⃣ Repository with Custom Query
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.Query;
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.JpaRepository;
import java.util.List;

public interface EmployeeRepository extends JpaRepository<Employee,Integer> {

    @Query("from Employee")
    List<Employee> getAllEmployees();

}

This query retrieves all employee records.

4️⃣ Custom Query with Condition

Example: Get employees from Sales department

@Query("from Employee where dept=:dname")
List<Employee> getEmployeesByDept(String dname);
5️⃣ Using the Method
List<Employee> list = repo.getEmployeesByDept("Sales");

for(Employee e : list){
    System.out.println(e.getEmpName());
}

Generated query:

select * from employee where dept='Sales'
6️⃣ Native SQL Query

Sometimes we use pure SQL instead of JPQL.

@Query(value="select * from employee where dept=?", nativeQuery=true)
List<Employee> getEmployeesByDept(String dept);

Here:

nativeQuery = true

means use SQL query instead of JPQL.

7️⃣ JPQL vs SQL
Feature	JPQL	Native SQL
Works on	Entity class	Database table
Example	from Employee	select * from employee
Portable	Yes	No
